# Native clients

ELVish has two mobile clients: **iOS** (`IOS/`) and **Android** (`flutter/elvish_mail/`). Both use the same `/api/` endpoints and session cookies as the browser.

## Normative source

The **browser implementation is the spec**. When implementing mobile features, match behavior from these web files:

| Area | Normative source |
|------|------------------|
| Compose (PGP + protected link) | `static/mail/compose.jsx` |
| Reply / Reply-all | `buildReplyComposeDraft` in `static/mail/mail-app.jsx` |
| Client-side filters | `static/mail/mail-filter-engine.js` |
| Key unlock | `static/auth/unlock.js`, `static/mail/unlock-modal.jsx` |

## Feature tiers (see [client-parity-roadmap.md](docs/client-parity-roadmap.md))

- **Tier 1** (mobile core): Auth, vault unlock, inbox read, triage, compose, reply, client filters
- **Tier 2**: Minimal settings UI
- **Tier 3** (web-only): Signup, full settings, admin, local search, attachments, HTML compose

## Crypto alignment

Both clients must match the browser's OpenPGP implementation:
- Same ECC curve (Curve25519) for identity keys
- Same KDF parameters for account key derivation
- Same SRP-6a parameters (see `cmd/srpvector` for test vectors)

Use the secure storage APIs (iOS Keychain, Android Keystore) for persisted key material.

## Development

```bash
make test-flutter    # analyze + unit tests
make test-ios        # macOS only; xcodebuild test
make check-clients   # both (iOS only on macOS)
```

Test against `http://127.0.0.1:8765` (iOS simulator) or `http://10.0.2.2:8765` (Android emulator).

## Do not

- Implement features beyond the current tier without updating the parity roadmap
- Diverge from browser crypto parameters without an ADR
- Enable push notification handlers before backend support exists (entitlement stub only)
- Add new Xcode capabilities without a matrix row in client-parity-roadmap.md
